SIMPLE: moderator
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Moderator
<hw>Mod"er*a`tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.: cf. F.
<ets>mod⟦eacute⟧rateur</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who, or that
which, moderates, restrains, or pacifies.</def> <rj><au>Sir W.
Raleigh.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Angling was . . . a <qex>moderator</qex> of passions.</q>
<rj><qau>Walton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The officer who presides over an assembly or
discussion to preserve order, propose questions, regulate the
proceedings, and declare the votes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>In the University of Oxford, an examiner for
moderations; at Cambridge, the superintendant of examinations for
degrees; at Dublin, either the first (senior) or second (junior) in rank
in an examination for the degree of Bachelor of Arts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A mechanical arrangement for regulating motion in a
machine, or producing equality of effect.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moderatorship</ent>⟦br⟧
